COMBINING ABBREVIATION MARK BAR ABOVE — The character above is frequently used as an abbreviation mark in Medieval (and Classical) manuscripts and inscriptions
column5578: normally standing for a nasal consonant ('n' or 'm') and sometimes referred to as 'nasal stroke'. We recommend the entity name ‘&bar;’ rather than the more cumbersome ‘&combovl;’. As a rule
column5580: i.e. they should connect with adjoining characters. In that way
column5581:
a continuous overline over more than one character can be displayed by a sequence of single-character overlines.

column5951:
U+034F ͏ COMBINING GRAPHEME JOINER is a Unicode character that has no visible glyph and is \"default ignorable\" by applications. Its name is a misnomer and does not describe its function: the character does not join graphemes.[1] Its purpose is to semantically separate characters that should not be considered digraphs as well as to block canonical reordering of combining marks during normalization.

"
column5983:
notes:"

COMBINING ABBREVIATION MARK ZIGZAG ABOVE

Used primarily (and extensively) in Nordic manuscripts to abbreviate er/ir (and 'r' for the word 'er').

The mark for 'er' is described in a 12th-century grammatical treatise preserved in the 14th-century manuscript AM 242 fol.:
column5985: but yet it is used-for the speeding-up and shortening of the writing-for various other letters
column5986: sometimes one and sometimes more. I use it most often for m
column5989:
when it has [this] shape: [see image]. On this (subject) I do not know more than a small (piece of) advice (I can give): let each one (abbreviate by means of the tittle as (far as he) finds suitable and comprehensible.\" (trans. Hreinn Benediktsson)

"

See also 034F COMBINING GRAPHEME JOINER.

Cf. Wikipedia:

The zero-width joiner (ZWJ
column9013: /ˈzwɪdʒ/;[1] rendered: ‍; HTML entity: &zwj; or &#8205;) is a non-printing character used in the computerized typesetting of writing systems in which the shape or positioning of a grapheme depends on its relation to other graphemes (complex scripts)
column9014: such as the Arabic script or any Indic script. Sometimes the Roman script is to be counted as complex
column9015: e.g. when using a Fraktur typeface. When placed between two characters that would otherwise not be connected
column9016:
a ZWJ causes them to be printed in their connected forms.
